{#
  narrate_diffusion.j2
  =====================
  Jinja2 prompt template for LLM-based narration of 1-D diffusion simulation
  results produced by nominal_drift.science.diffusion_engine.

  Variables injected by narration.render_narration_prompt()
  ----------------------------------------------------------
  alloy_designation       str    e.g. "316L", "2205", "IN718"
  alloy_matrix            str    e.g. "austenite", "ferrite", "duplex"
  element                 str    diffusing species symbol, e.g. "Cr", "N", "C"
  ht_summary              str    human-readable heat-treatment description
  c_bulk_wt_pct           float  bulk / nominal concentration [wt%]
  c_sink_wt_pct           float  boundary sink concentration [wt%]
  min_concentration_wt_pct float minimum concentration anywhere in domain [wt%]
  depletion_depth_nm      float|None  depth of depletion zone [nm], or None
  warnings                list[str]   solver diagnostic messages (may be empty)
  user_label              str|None    optional short run label from db_record
  user_notes              str|None    optional free-form notes from db_record

  Rendering notes
  ---------------
  trim_blocks and lstrip_blocks are enabled in the Environment so that
  block tags do not insert extra blank lines into the rendered output.
#}
You are interpreting the output of a 1-D continuum diffusion simulation.
Produce a concise engineering interpretation of the results below.

=== ALLOY AND SIMULATION CONTEXT ===
Alloy designation   : {{ alloy_designation }}
Matrix type         : {{ alloy_matrix }}
Diffusing species   : {{ element }}
Heat treatment      : {{ ht_summary }}
{% if user_label %}
Run label           : {{ user_label }}
{% endif %}
{% if user_notes %}
User notes          : {{ user_notes }}
{% endif %}

=== NUMERICAL RESULTS (deterministic solver output — do not modify) ===
Bulk concentration     (C_bulk)  = {{ c_bulk_wt_pct | round(4) }} wt%
Sink concentration     (C_sink)  = {{ c_sink_wt_pct | round(4) }} wt%
Minimum [{{ element }}] in domain          = {{ min_concentration_wt_pct | round(4) }} wt%
{% if depletion_depth_nm is not none %}
Depletion depth                  = {{ depletion_depth_nm | round(1) }} nm
{% else %}
Depletion depth                  = not determined (concentration did not cross sink threshold within modelled domain)
{% endif %}

{% if warnings %}
=== SOLVER WARNINGS ===
{% for w in warnings %}
  - {{ w }}
{% endfor %}

{% endif %}
=== MODEL ASSUMPTIONS ===
  - Fick's second law, 1-D Cartesian geometry, Crank-Nicolson finite-difference scheme
  - Arrhenius diffusivity evaluated at hold temperature; assumed constant within each isothermal segment
  - Dirichlet boundary at x = 0 (instantaneous sink; models grain boundary, interface, or free surface)
  - Dirichlet boundary at x = x_max (bulk reservoir; fixed at C_bulk)
  - THIS IS A CONTINUUM MODEL — it is NOT an atomistic or molecular-dynamics simulation
  - THIS IS NOT a full precipitation kinetics or phase-transformation model
  - Diffusivity data are literature-derived; experimental validation is required before applying results to safety-critical assessments
  - Results represent one diffusing species under the stated conditions; interactions with other species are not modelled

=== YOUR TASK ===
Write a concise engineering interpretation of these results (3 to 5 sentences).

You MUST follow all of these rules:
1. Describe in plain engineering language what the concentration profile result means physically for [{{ element }}] in a {{ alloy_matrix }}-type material.
2. Comment on the minimum concentration and, if available, the depletion depth. Relate these to any engineering significance (e.g. proximity to a corrosion or degradation threshold, extent of enrichment or depletion, comparison of diffusion rate).
3. Mention at least one key model assumption or limitation the reader should bear in mind when interpreting these results.
4. Do NOT invent any number that does not appear in the context above.
5. Do NOT claim this is an atomistic simulation, a molecular-dynamics result, or a validated precipitation kinetics model.
6. Keep the language generic and applicable to [{{ element }}] in {{ alloy_matrix }}-type materials generally — do not assume a specific application domain unless one is stated in user_notes.
{% if warnings %}
7. Acknowledge the solver warning(s) briefly and advise whether the user should consider extending the simulation domain or adjusting parameters.
{% endif %}
